:686,"geo":693,"country":60,"region":61,"settlement":506,"repository":697,"idno":698,"textLang":700,"facsimile":702,"provenance":688,"letterHeights":707,"publications":708,"zotero":713,"keywords":718,"html":724},"ISic001190","The municipium of the Haluntini honours Gnaeus Pollienus",{"_":148},{"_":13,"ana":14,"ref":15},{"_":254,"ana":155,"ref":19},{"_":663,"ana":664,"ref":665},"breccia (local)","#material.stone.breccia","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/material/lod/73.html",{"ana":274},{"layout":668},{"p":669,"rs":670,"damage":671},"The text occupies five lines over the upper part of the front face.",{"_":28,"ana":29,"ref":30},{"ana":672},"#text_condition.deteriorated",{"lettering":674,"dimensions":675},"Regular letters with a fairly square module, simply engraved without serifs. Alpha has broken bar; Kappa has full length arms; Mu has vertical first and last, with mid-strokes only descending half-way; omicron is full size; Pi has full length verticals, and slightly overlapping horizontal bar; omega is slightly open and nearly circular, with horizontal tails/feet.",[676,679],{"type":35,"l":677,"from":37,"to":492,"h":678,"unit":38},"Line 1-5","30",{"type":40,"l":680,"from":37,"to":42,"unit":38},"Interlineation line 1 to 2 ",{"_":682,"notBefore":683,"notAfter":684,"evidence":685},"The use of the term 'municipium' in Greek places this text almost certainly after the grant of Latin rights to Sicily by Julius Caesar (probably 46 BCE), but equally the use of Greek implies a date not later than the early Augustan period. The lettering is compatible with a late Hellenistic date.",-46,-1,"textual-context",[687,690],{"_":688,"type":50,"ref":689},"Haluntium","http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/462228",{"_":691,"type":54,"ref":692},"San Marco d'Alunzio","http://sws.geonames.org/2523425",[694],[695,696],38.07261,14.70093,{"_":508,"role":64,"ref":509},{"_":699,"type":210},"8814",{"_":513,"mainLang":514,"languages":701},[513],{"n":71,"url":703,"height":704,"width":705,"desc":706,"sur